{"title_page": "Karimata Islands", "text_new": "{{Unreferenced|date=July 2008}}\n[[File:Karimata.jpg|right|thumb|Karimata Island]]\n\nThe '''Karimata Islands''' are a chain of small islands off the west coast of [[Indonesia]]n [[Borneo]], the largest of which is (Pulau) Karimata, being about {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} across (east-west), and situated at {{coord|1|37|S|108|53|E|}}. It is part of [[Kayong Utara]] in Indonesia. Karimata has a wide range of [[ecosystem]]s, from [[mangroves]] and [[tropical rain forest]] in the lowlands to [[montane shrubland]] on the summit of the c.{{convert|1000|m|0|abbr=on}} mountain (a spectacular example of the [[Massenerhebung effect]]).  The mountain is composed of [[granite]].  A substantial population of [[cave swiftlet]]s has historically been the source of birds nests for [[Swiftlet|birds nest soup]], but has decreased recently to near [[Local extinction|extirpation]], due to [[Overexploitation|overharvesting]] by non-indigenous collectors who have been arriving from the mainland.\nA number of small villages are situated on the coast, the largest of which is [[Padang, Borneo|Padang]], on the eastern tip of the island.  The island is renowned by inhabitants of the west coast of [[Kalimantan]] to have a serious [[malaria]] problem.\n\nDutch explorers visited the island a number of times, and there have been at least two recent visits by biologists.  The island is classified as a nature reserve by the Indonesian government, but there has been no management of the area. There are rumours of plans for large tourist developments.\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Islands of Kalimantan]]\n\n\n{{WKalimantan-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=July 2008}}\n[[File:Karimata.jpg|right|thumb|Karimata Island]]\n\nThe '''Karimata Islands''' are a chain of small islands off the west coast of [[Indonesia]]n [[Borneo]], the largest of which is (Pulau) Karimata, being about {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} across (east-west), and situated at {{coord|1|37|S|108|53|E|}}. It is part of [[Kayong Utara]] in Indonesia. Karimata has a wide range of [[ecosystem]]s, from [[mangroves]] and [[tropical rain forest]] in the lowlands to [[montane shrubland]] on the summit of the c.{{convert|1000|m|0|abbr=on}} mountain (a spectacular example of the [[Massenerhebung effect]]).  The mountain is composed of [[granite]].  A substantial population of [[cave swiftlet]]s has historically been the source of birds nests for [[Swiftlet|birds nest soup]], but has decreased recently to near [[Local extinction|extirpation]], due to [[Overexploitation|overharvesting]] by non-indigenous collectors who have been arriving from the mainland.\nA number of small villages are situated on the coast, the largest of which is [[Padang, Borneo|Padang]], on the eastern tip of the island.  The island is renowned by inhabitants of the west coast of [[Kalimantan]] to have a serious [[malaria]] problem.\n\nDutch explorers visited the island a number of times, and there have been at least two recent visits by biologists.  The island is classified as a nature reserve by the Indonesian government, but there has been no management of the area. There are rumours of plans for large tourist developments.\n\n[[Category:Archipelagoes of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Islands of Kalimantan]]\n\n\n{{WKalimantan-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karimata_Islands"}
{"title_page": "Magneto-Electric Spin-Orbit", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}\n{{notability|date=December 2018}}\n{{advert|date=December 2018}}\n{{primary sources|date=December 2018}} }}\n\n'''Magneto-Electric Spin-Orbit''' ('''MESO''') is a technology for constructing scalable [[integrated circuit]]s. MESO devices operate by the coupling of the [[Magnetoelectric effect]] with the spin orbit coupling effect.<ref name=\"nature\" /> Specifically, the mangetoelectric effect will induce a change in [[Magnetization]] within the device due to an induced electric field, which can then be read out by the spin orbit coupling component.<ref name=\"MESO experimental demo\" /> This mechanism is analogous to how a [[CMOS]] device operates with the source, gate and drain electrodes work together to form a logic gate. Compared to CMOS, MESO circuits require less energy for switching, lower operating voltage, and feature a higher integration density,<ref name=\"nature\" /> making them ideal candidates to replace CMOS based devices in the future. The technology is currently in development by [[Intel]] and [[University of California, Berkeley]].<ref name=\"designnews\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!   \n! Feature Size [nm]<ref name=\"nature\" />\n! Supply Voltage [mV]<ref name=\"nature\" />\n! Switching Energy [J]<ref name=\"nature\" />\n|-\n! scope=row | CMOS\n| 10 || 100 - 700|| 300x10<sup>-18</sup>\n|-\n! scope=row | MESO \n| 10 || 10 - 100 || 10x10<sup>-18</sup>\n|}\n\n\n== References ==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"nature\">{{cite journal\n| doi=10.1038/s41586-018-0770-2\n| pmid=30510160\n| title=Scalable energy-efficient magnetoelectric spin\u2013orbit logic\n| journal=Nature\n| year=2018\n| last1=Manipatruni\n| first1=Sasikanth\n| last2=Nikonov\n| first2=Dmitri E.\n| last3=Lin\n| first3=Chia-Ching\n| last4=Gosavi\n| first4=Tanay A.\n| last5=Liu\n| first5=Huichu\n| last6=Prasad\n| first6=Bhagwati\n| last7=Huang\n| first7=Yen-Lin\n| last8=Bonturim\n| first8=Everton\n| last9=Ramesh\n| first9=Ramamoorthy\n| last10=Young\n| first10=Ian A.\n| volume=565\n| issue=7737\n| pages=35\u201342\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"designnews\">\n{{cite web\n|title=How the New Quantum 'MESO' Architecture Could Replace CMOS\n|url=https://www.designnews.com/electronics-test/how-new-quantum-meso-architecture-could-replace-cmos/52879693360067?ADTRK=UBM&elq_mid=7186&elq_cid=889505\n|access-date=2019-07-27\n|publisher=DesignNews\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"MESO experimental demo\">{{cite journal\n| doi=10.1109/IEDM19573.2019.8993620\n| title=Experimental demonstration of integrated magnetoelectric and spin-orbit building blocks implementing energy-efficient logic\n| journal=IEEE Meeting\n| year=2019\n| last1=Lin\n| first1=Chia-Ching \n| last2= Gosavi\n| first2=Tanay\n| last3=Nikonov\n| first3=Dmitri E.\n| last4=Huang\n| first4=Yen-Lin\n| last5=Prasad\n| first5=Bhagwati\n| last6=Choi\n| first6=WonYoung\n| last7=Pham\n| first7=Van Tuong\n| last8=Groen\n| first8=Inge\n| last9=Chen\n| first9=Jun-Yang\n| last10=DC\n| first10=Mahendra\n| last11=Liu\n| first11=Huichu\n| last12=Oguz\n| first12=Kaan\n| last13=Walker\n| first13=Emily S\n| last14=Plombon\n| first14=John\n| last15=Buford\n| first15=Benjamin\n| last16=Naylor\n| first16=Carl H.\n| last17=Wang\n| first17=Jian-Ping\n| last18=Casanova\n| first18=Felix\n| last19=Ramesh\n| first19=Ramamoorthy\n| last20=Young\n| first20=Ian A.\n| pages=37.3.1-37.3.4.\n}}</ref>\n</references>\n\n[[category:Spintronics]]\n\n{{Electronics-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=December 2018}}\n{{refimprove|date=December 2018}}\n{{notability|date=December 2018}}\n{{advert|date=December 2018}}\n{{primary sources|date=December 2018}} }}\n\n'''Magneto-Electric Spin-Orbit''' ('''MESO''') is a technology for constructing scalable [[integrated circuit]]s. MESO devices operate by the coupling of the [[Magnetoelectric effect]] with the spin orbit coupling effect.<ref name=\"nature\" />. Specifically, the mangetoelectric effect will induce a change in [[Magnetization]] within the device due to an induced electric field, which can then be read out by the spin orbit coupling component<ref name=\"MESO experimental demo\" />. This mechanism is analogous to how a [[CMOS]] device operates with the source, gate and drain electrodes work together to form a logic gate. Compared to CMOS, MESO circuits require less energy for switching, lower operating voltage, and feature a higher integration density<ref name=\"nature\" />, making them ideal candidates to replace CMOS based devices in the future. The technology is currently in development by [[Intel]] and [[University of California, Berkeley]]<ref name=\"designnews\" />\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!   \n! Feature Size [nm]<ref name=\"nature\" />\n! Supply Voltage [mV]<ref name=\"nature\" />\n! Switching Energy [J]<ref name=\"nature\" />\n|-\n! scope=row | CMOS\n| 10 || 100 - 700|| 300x10<sup>-18</sup>\n|-\n! scope=row | MESO \n| 10 || 10 - 100 || 10x10<sup>-18</sup>\n|}\n\n\n== References ==\n<references>\n<ref name=\"nature\">{{cite journal\n| doi=10.1038/s41586-018-0770-2\n| pmid=30510160\n| title=Scalable energy-efficient magnetoelectric spin\u2013orbit logic\n| journal=Nature\n| year=2018\n| last1=Manipatruni\n| first1=Sasikanth\n| last2=Nikonov\n| first2=Dmitri E.\n| last3=Lin\n| first3=Chia-Ching\n| last4=Gosavi\n| first4=Tanay A.\n| last5=Liu\n| first5=Huichu\n| last6=Prasad\n| first6=Bhagwati\n| last7=Huang\n| first7=Yen-Lin\n| last8=Bonturim\n| first8=Everton\n| last9=Ramesh\n| first9=Ramamoorthy\n| last10=Young\n| first10=Ian A.\n| volume=565\n| issue=7737\n| pages=35\u201342\n}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"designnews\">\n{{cite web\n|title=How the New Quantum 'MESO' Architecture Could Replace CMOS\n|url=https://www.designnews.com/electronics-test/how-new-quantum-meso-architecture-could-replace-cmos/52879693360067?ADTRK=UBM&elq_mid=7186&elq_cid=889505\n|access-date=2019-07-27\n|publish